# Online Store — Data Analysis Project

End-to-end data analysis project built during my internship, covering data cleaning, exploratory analysis, customer segmentation (RFM), cohort retention, revenue forecasting, and an interactive dashboard — all built in Python from a raw e-commerce orders dataset.

## Project Overview

The dataset contains 1,200 orders across 1,189 unique customers and 7 products. The goal was to clean the raw data, extract business-relevant metrics, and surface actionable insights for a hypothetical online store — going beyond basic summary stats into segmentation, retention, and trend forecasting.

**Key insight:** the store's repeat purchase rate is very low (under 1% of customers placed more than one order, contributing only ~1.5% of revenue). That single number is the biggest growth lever in the dataset — most of the analysis and recommendations below trace back to it.


## Tools & Libraries

Python, pandas, NumPy, Matplotlib, Seaborn, SciPy (`stats.linregress`, `zscore`), Plotly (`graph_objects`, `subplots`).

## Methodology

- **Data cleaning:** missing coupon codes filled, dates parsed, duplicates and duplicate order IDs checked, text columns standardized, price mismatches flagged.
- **Outlier detection:** IQR method (1.5× IQR) as the primary flag, cross-checked against a Z-score method (|z| > 3) since the two can disagree on skewed distributions.
- **RFM segmentation:** customers scored on Recency, Frequency, and Monetary value using quartile-based binning (`pd.qcut`), then mapped into 8 named segments (Champion, Loyal, At Risk, Lost, etc.).
- **Cohort analysis:** customers grouped by first-purchase month, tracking retention percentage in each subsequent month.
- **Forecasting:** simple linear regression on monthly revenue. The model's R² is low (~0.09), meaning the trend line explains only a small share of month-to-month variation — the 3-month forecast is reported with that caveat rather than presented as a reliable prediction. This was an intentional choice: a forecast number without an honesty check on fit quality is more misleading than useful.
- **Product profitability:** estimated using assumed margin percentages (not actual cost data), clearly labeled as estimates in the report.

## Key Results

- **Total Revenue:** ₹1,264,761.96 across 1,200 orders
- **Average Order Value:** ₹1,053.97 (median ₹823.62)
- **Top Product:** Chair (highest revenue contributor)
- **Top 20% of customers** drive **45.3%** of total revenue
- **Repeat customers:** 11 out of 1,189 (0.9%), contributing only 1.5% of revenue
- **Best sales day:** Sunday
- **8 IQR outlier orders** flagged for manual review

